European Defense and European Solidarity
PRAG: Perhaps it is due to the experience of a man who had to endure forty years of communist rule, and before that, the occupation by the Nazis.
Perhaps it is due to the experience of living in a country in the heart of Europe, a place that for centuries has been a crossroads of intellectual currents, geopolitical interests, and confrontations in Europe.
Perhaps all these factors, combined, have led me to come to the conclusion that Europe represents a single political unit, whose security is indivisible.
The notion that there could be two Europes forever – one democratic, stable, prosperous, and integrated, and the other less democratic, less stable, less prosperous, and isolated – is a misconception.
This is like heating up one part of a room while it remains cold in another part.
There is only one Europe, despite its diversity.
Every significant event echoes across Europe.
For Europe to become united, for the European Union to embrace the new post-communist democracies  which is in the interest of Europe  a series of essential tasks must be addressed, both within the new democracies and within the European and Atlantic communities.
First, Europe must foster community in the post-communist countries by restoring civil society.
Denn eine lebendige Gesellschaft kann nicht von oben wiederaufgebaut werden.
Europe must therefore help its new democracies become an organic part of a common continental commitment to deepen and strengthen civil society.
The more diverse European civil society structures become and the more they are interconnected, the better equipped the new democracies will be for EU membership and the more stable they will be as states.
To achieve this, Europe must encourage the new democracies to transfer various solidarity tasks to self-governing institutions and nonprofit or public service organizations.
The deeper the level of redistribution, the more transparent and economical it will be; and the better it will address those social needs that central authorities cannot recognize.
The social solidarity will become more authentic when it is closely connected to individuals or their associations.
An authentic solidarity among people, social groups, settlements, and regions is also the most secure foundation for those forms of solidarity that can only be exercised by states.
A bitter chapter in modern European history was the appeasement policy, which renounced European solidarity, leading to the capitulation at Munich.
This experience remains a strong call for vigilance.
Evil must be confronted as soon as it appears, but it is not enough if governments act alone.
Denn Regierungspolitik erwächst aus den Empfindungen der Zivilgesellschaft, aus dem Volk.
Besorgnis um die Sicherheit ist in der Tat eine Manifestation gesellschaftlicher Solidarität.
Die EU arbeitet intensiv an einem neuen Konzept ihrer Sicherheitspolitik.
Es sollte sich durch eine Fähigkeit auszeichnen, rasch zu entscheiden und gemeinschaftliche Entscheidungen schnell in die Tat umzusetzen  Reformen, die die jüngsten Entwicklungen in Jugoslawien als notwendig erwiesen.
Die Intervention der NATO im vergangenen Jahr hat gezeigt, dass der Respekt für menschliches Leben und menschliche Freiheit sowie die Belange gesamteuropäischer Sicherheit Interventionen außerhalb der EU-Grenzen erfordern.
Je stronger the mandate for such an action is, the better.
Unfortunately, there may be situations where the UN mandate might not be available, even though an intervention is in the interest of many people, indeed of all of Europe, and even of human civilization.
Until recently, Europe was poorly prepared for this alternative.
It is now better prepared at least psychologically.
This psychological readiness should be used to promote Europe's material and technical readiness.
But there is still much more needed in the field of preventive security, but it is also necessary for this security to reflect the values of Europe's extended civil society.
Tens of thousands of lives and enormous amounts of material could have been saved in Kosovo, in Bosnia and Herzegovina, and in other parts of former Yugoslavia if the international community had acted at the onset of the conflicts.
Despite warnings about impending horrors, actions were only taken timidly.
These shortcomings were due to a variety of individual domestic political interests as well as a lack of willingness to take risks for a good cause.
Without American energy, the international community would indeed still have watched the horrors in Kosovo unfold.
Europe cannot be dependent on the USA forever, especially not regarding European problems.
It must be able to find solutions on its own.
It is inconceivable that the EU can remain a respected part of the world order if it fails to find ways to protect human rights, not only on its own territory, but also in regions that may join it one day.
Such an expansion of the EU is only feasible if it moves hand in hand with a bold reform of EU institutions.
I hope confidently that the intergovernmental conference on institutional reform will present practical proposals for advancing the union.
But I consider this as the beginning of a process that will take perhaps decades and should be guided by a lasting effort to accelerate and make the EU decision-making more transparent.
An issue related to the institutional reform is how to give smaller states the certainty that they will not be simply overpowered by the larger ones, while still taking the size of individual states into due consideration.
A possible solution could be the establishment of a second chamber of the European Parliament; the members of this second chamber would be elected from their own ranks by the parliaments of the member states and not directly.
The first chamber of the EU – i.e., the current Parliament – would therefore reflect the size of the individual member states, while the second chamber, with the same number of representatives for each state, would increase equality.
At some point, these changes will require the EU to have a clear, understandable constitution – a text that all European children could learn.
Eine solche Verfassung benötigt zwei Teile.
Teil eins würde die Rechte und Pflichten sowohl der europäischen Bürger als auch der Staaten, die zugrundeliegenden Werte und die Bedeutung und Ziele der Integration festlegen.
Teil zwei würde die zentralen Institutionen der EU, ihre prinzipiellen Befugnisse und ihre Beziehungen zueinander beschreiben.
Solch ein Grundgesetz würde nicht eine automatische Umwandlung der jetzigen Union in den föderalen Überstaat bedeuten, der von Euroskeptikern befürchtet wird.
Es würde jedoch den Bürgern in einem sich integrierenden Europa dabei helfen, zu erkennen, wofür die EU steht, sie besser zu verstehen, die Bedeutung der EU für ihr Leben zu sehen und, folglich, sich mit ihr zu identifizieren.
